G
∗(ω) = G′(ω) + iG′′(ω), (2.5)
with imaginary unit i = √−1, time t, lag time τ , and angular frequency
ω = f/2π. Clearly the modulus and the compliance are inverse - a stiffer
material has higher modulus and lower compliance. The complex modulus
has a real part, the elastic (or storage) modulus G′, and an imaginary part,
the viscous (or loss) modulus G′′.
Using the complex modulus to describe a material response has the primary
advantage that the elastic and viscous components can be easily separated
