scattered photon wavevectors. The cosine term arises from the geometry
of the incident wavevectors (shown in Figure 2.7a).
An inelastic scattering event gives rise to either a Stokes shift in the case
of the photon losing momentum to a phonon or an anti-Stokes shift in the
case of a photon gaining momentum from a phonon. For Stokes scattered
light, the wavevectors may be drawn as in Figure 2.7. Consider first the
wavevectors of the two interacting particles, followed by the frequency shift
